</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,260,285]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Remarks.</emphasis>
This is an outstanding species, whose taxonomic position remains uncertain (Stonis 
<emphasis box="[1269,1319,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1333,1412,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">in prep</emphasis>
.). The wing venation of this species was studied neither by 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[801,1122,295,320]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson (2000)</bibRefCitation>
nor us, in order to preserve the already badly damaged 
<typeStatus box="[459,566,332,357]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">lectotype</typeStatus>
. The head is on a pin and shows a rubbed frontal tuft and indistinct collar; the thorax and wings are pinned separately in a gelatin capsule; the scaling of thorax and wings is well preserved; but damage to the thorax precludes repinning (
<bibRefCitation author="Stonis" box="[630,845,404,429]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refString="Stonis, J. R., Diskus, A., Remeikis, A., Gerulaitis, V. &amp; Karsholt, O. (2016 d) Leaf-mining Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) from record high altitudes: documenting an entire new fauna in the Andean paramo and puna. Monograph. Zootaxa, 4181 (1), 1 - 94. http: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4181.1.1" type="journal article" year="2016" yearSuffix="d">
Stonis 
<emphasis box="[708,757,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al</emphasis>
. 2016d
</bibRefCitation>
: 67).
</paragraph>
